Read list of images with different colour channels¶

In [2]:
def show_images(images, gray=None):
    """
    This is an utility function to show multiple images with different colour maps

    :param images - An images list
    :param gray - A flag to set default value for matplotlib imshow colour map. If the image
                  shape is 2( i.e binary image) then cmap value will be "gray"
    :return: Nothing
    """
    rows = (len(images)+1)//2
    plt.figure(figsize=(11, 11))
    for idx, img in enumerate(images):
        plt.subplot(rows, 2, idx+1)
        # if the image is binary then it'll be printed as grayscale, otherwise colour map
        # will be ignored
        plt.imshow(img, cmap="gray" if len(img.shape) == 2 else gray)
        plt.xticks([])
        plt.yticks([])

    plt.show()

Select yellow and white colours from given test images¶

OpenCV cv.inRange function can be used to filter image spaces¶
References:¶
  • RGB color picker
  • Thresholding Operations using inRange
In [4]:
def select_rgb_white_yellow(img):
    # white mask
    lower_bound = np.uint8([220,220,220])
    upper_bound = np.uint8([255,255,255])
    w_mask = cv2.inRange(img, lower_bound, upper_bound)

    # yellow masked
    lower_bound = np.uint8([190, 190,0])
    y_mask = cv2.inRange(img, lower_bound, upper_bound)

    # combine the masks
    mask = cv2.bitwise_or(w_mask, y_mask)
    return cv2.bitwise_and(img, img,mask=mask)

show_images(list(map(select_rgb_white_yellow, test_images)))

HSL and HSV Colour Filters¶

  • H- Hue: Hue is a degree on the color wheel from 0 to 360. 0 is red, 120 is green, 240 is blue.
  • S- Saturation: Saturation is a percentage value; 0% means a shade of gray and 100% is the full color.
  • L - Lightness: Lightness is also a percentage; 0% is black, 100% is white.

In [5]:
def rgb_to_hsv(img):
    return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2HLS)

def select_white_yellow(img):
    # convert RGB colour space to HSL colour space
    converted_img = rgb_to_hsv(img)
    # white colour mask
    lower_bound = np.uint8([0, 200, 0])
    upper_bound = np.uint8([255, 255, 255])
    w_mask = cv2.inRange(converted_img, lower_bound, upper_bound)
    # yellow colour mask
    lower_bound = np.uint8([10, 0, 100])
    y_mask = cv2.inRange(converted_img, lower_bound, upper_bound)

    # combine the mask
    mask = cv2.bitwise_or(w_mask, y_mask)
    return cv2.bitwise_and(img, img, mask=mask)

w_y_images = list(map(select_white_yellow, test_images))
show_images(w_y_images)

Combine masked filters the yellow and white clearly.

def grayscale(img):
    """
    This function is used to convert RGB images to gray scale iamges
    :param img: input image
    :return: gray scaled image
    """
    return cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)

gray_scaled_images = list(map(grayscale,w_y_images))
show_images(gray_scaled_images)

def apply_smoothing(img, kernel_size = 11):
    """
    This function is used to
    :param img: gray scaled input image
    :param kernel_size:
    :return:
    """
    return cv2.GaussianBlur(img, (kernel_size, kernel_size), 0)

blurred_images = list(map(lambda img: apply_smoothing(img), gray_scaled_images))
show_images(blurred_images)

Detect edges using OpenCV Canny edge detector¶

def detect_edges(img, low_threshold = 50, high_threshold=150):
    """

    :param img:
    :param low_threshold:
    :param high_threshold:
    :return:
    """
    return cv2.Canny(img,low_threshold, high_threshold)

edge_detected_images = list(map(lambda img: detect_edges(img), blurred_images))
show_images(edge_detected_images)

Select interest region¶

In [11]:
def region_of_interest(img, vertices):
    """
    Applies an image mask.

    Only keeps the region of the image defined by the polygon
    formed from `vertices`. The rest of the image is set to black.
    `vertices` should be a numpy array of integer points.
    """
    #defining a blank mask to start with
    mask = np.zeros_like(img)

    #defining a 3 channel or 1 channel color to fill the mask with depending on the input image
    if len(img.shape) > 2:
        channel_count = img.shape[2]  # i.e. 3 or 4 depending on your image
        ignore_mask_color = (255,) * channel_count
    else:
        ignore_mask_color = 255

    #filling pixels inside the polygon defined by "vertices" with the fill color
    cv2.fillPoly(mask, vertices, ignore_mask_color)

    #returning the image only where mask pixels are nonzero
    masked_image = cv2.bitwise_and(img, mask)
    return masked_image

def select_region(img):
    """

    :param img:
    :return:
    """
    imshape = img.shape
    # this can be inefficient
    vertices = np.array([[(0,imshape[0]),(450, 290), (490, 290), (imshape[1],imshape[0])]], dtype=np.int32)
    return region_of_interest(img, vertices)

roi_images = list(map(select_region, edge_detected_images))
show_images(roi_images)

def hough_lines(image):
    """
    `image` should be the output of a Canny transform.

    Returns hough lines (not the image with lines)
    """
    return cv2.HoughLinesP(image, rho=1, theta=np.pi/180, threshold=20, minLineLength=20, maxLineGap=300)

list_of_lines = list(map(hough_lines, roi_images))
In [13]:
def draw_lines(img, lines, thickness=2, make_copy=True):
    # the lines returned by cv2.HoughLinesP has the shape (-1, 1, 4)
    if make_copy:
        img = np.copy(img) # don't want to modify the original
    for line in lines:
        for x1,y1,x2,y2 in line:
            cv2.line(img, (x1, y1), (x2, y2), [255, 0, 0], thickness)
    return img

line_images =[]
for img, lines in zip(test_images,list_of_lines):
    line_images.append(draw_lines(img, lines))

show_images(line_images)

def process_image(img):
    w_y_img = select_white_yellow(img)
    gray_img = grayscale(w_y_img)
    smooth_gray = apply_smoothing(gray_img)
    edges = detect_edges(smooth_gray)
    roi_img = select_region(edges)
    lines = hough_lines(roi_img)
    return draw_lines(img, lines)

    white_clip.write_videofile(out_dir+output, audio=False)
    return white_clip

Averaging & Extrapolation Lane Lines¶

Averaging Lines¶

There are multiple lines detected for a lane line. We should come up with an averaged line for that.

Extrapolation Lines¶

Since we are expecting a triangular shape left and right lines, slop of the left must positive and slop of the right must negative. And, there are lane lines not detected fully. Therefore we should extrapolate the line to cover full lane length.
